    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-07-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-07-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="265"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d265">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.9412Anti-War/156</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Japanese Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Debuchi</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-24">July 24,
                            1929</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                    receipt of your note of July 24, 1929, transmitting the Declaration of the
                    Imperial Government made on June 27 of this year that the phraseology “in the
                    names of their respective peoples”, appearing in Article I of the treaty for the
                    renunciation of war, signed at Paris on August 27, 1928, viewed in the light of
                    the provisions of the Imperial Constitution, is understood to be inapplicable in
                    so far as Japan is concerned.</p>
                <p>Note is taken of your statement that the Declaration was made for the purpose of
                    dispelling any doubt in relation to the Constitution of Japan, elucidating, as
                    it does, the construction placed by the Japanese Government on the phraseology
                    in question.</p>
                <p>I shall be happy, in compliance with the request which you make in your note to
                    send a copy thereof, together with a copy of the Declaration, to each of the
                    other High Contracting Parties, as well as to each of the Governments which have
                    adhered or which may hereafter adhere to the treaty.<note n="35"
                        xml:id="d265fn35">The treaty was proclaimed by the President of the United
                        States on July 24, 1929.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry L. Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
